{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_jordan_ver01/data/sn91068401/00332892782/1938010801/0046.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE SIX\nA Grid Star Tackles a House\nSix persons were sleeping in the room inf: which tcis uriven b*\nFrancis Hause, star tackle of Vanderbilt University, cras.,ea a.\nville Tenn. Out of control, the machine hurdled a six-foot ditcn. The\nentire house was wrecked by the impact, but no one, not even the driver,\nwas seriously injured. (Central Press)\nSenate Body Hears Knudsen\nv-:V-:: Y'x^J\nSenator Vandenberg of Michigan, is shown greeting William S. Knudsen,\npresident of the General Motors Corporation, which recently laid oft\n30,000 workers, when the latter appeared to testify before the Senate\nUnemployment Committee in Washington. After the hearing Knudsen\ncalled on President Roosevelt at the White House.\n(Central Press)\nStirs Japan\nH\n'l J|P^\nj\u00a3,- t*.\nksafcafi\u00dfa^fc'-\nYoshiki Okada\nvoluntary exile?\nStirring Tokio, Yoshiki Okada,\nbest known of Japan\u2019s stage and\nscreen actresses, fled with a Com\nmunist sweetheart, Ryokic'ni Sugi\nmoto, into Soviet territory by\ncrossing the Soviet Russian-Jap\nanese border on Sakhalin island.\nThe move is tantamount to exil\ning themselves for the remainded\nof their lives. Sugimoto, a writer,\nhas served a brief prison term for\nalleged anti-government activities.\nMiss Okada was billed for a per\nformance in one of the leading\ntheaters in Tokio this month.\nfttcAtt NUMSKUU.\nDEAR. NOAH= IF I LIVED iN\nCANADA AND HAD A HOME\nIN the: states, would\nHAVE. TO CROSS THE\nOOR.DEK TO PAPER- THE\nCEII1 NS 1\nc.h.ceowe halifav, n.s.\nPEAK- NOAH WHEN 1 7A\nLatins currant pie,\nSHOULD I USE A\nRUBBER. FORK to AVOID\n\u00a9ettins a shock\nMR.S. 2.ELDA EATON\nUl STANLEY, IOWA.\nDONV FCRGET FOLKS THE\nNUMB notion season is open\nFights for Job\nift\n\nRobert Lee Tudor, newly \u201celected\u201d\nNew York\u2019s city clerk, is determined\nto hold his job, despite the fact that\nopposition parties and the Mayor\nstate it is all a mistake. Opposition\nparty members hold that Tudor,\nwho received 13 out of the 26 council\nvotes is not elected, because 14 votes\nare necessary. Meanwhile, he goes\nto work at 9 every morning.\n(Central Press)\nF. D. R. Cook in Film?\nElizabeth McDuffie\nA screen test has been made of\nElizabeth McDuffie, cook at the\nWhite House, for a part in the\ncoming production, \u201cGone With\nthe Wind\u201d. It seems everybody\npossible has been, mentioned for\ntwo years for a part in this film,\nHENDERSON, (N. C.) DAILY DISPATCH, SATURDAY, JANUARY 8, 1938\nGloria Vanderbilt Grows Up\nill\n'\u2022;&ss s&s&s\u00a3>\nm\nMjH|g\n.^^fflM\u00dfraH\u00dfHWW\u00df|l|B|l|\nPpr^' MMHHH\n:w\u00df> ;X. WlfflllWTiffTlWSil l iHlll^Bnliffl*mir^B^lll\u00dflllMl\u00bb\u2018 J HliM\u00dfa\ng :h\nThirteen-year-old Gloria Vanderbilt, long-time object of custody battles\nbetween her mother and her aunt, Mrs. Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney, is\npictured at a New Year dance in New York with an unidentified Green\nvale School lad. The gown she is wearing is a gift from her mother.\n(Central. Pr'si)\nA Nazi Children\u2019s Hour\nDr. Joseph Goebbels may be dictator to the German press, but to his\nyoung daughter, Hilde, he is just \u201cvater.\u201d Goebbels is shown with her as\nhe attended a children\u2019s party and gave a propaganda address, broadcast\nto the country. Note the microphone, camouflaged w T ith pine boughs,\non the table. (Central Press)\nPlanning G. O. P. Program\ni t ||||||mM |||M\nMiss Jane Todd, Assemblywoman from Westchester County, is shown\nwith William S. Murray, Republican State chairman, discussing the vari\nous aspects of the legislative program to be considered by the Republican\nState Committee in Albany, N. Y. They were snapped as they awaited\nthe opening of the 1938 session of the state legislature.\n(Central Press)\nA #50,000 Bet\n:-88&$\u00a7r/ Jyggjiy\n\"\u2019t\nEileen Wenzel, who got an award of\n$40,774 in 1936 for the loss of her\nbeauty in an accident, will risk\nSI,OOO of her money against fifty\n;thousand of Tommy Manville\u2019s dol\nlars on the outcome of the Farr-\nBraddock fight. She likes Farr,\nManville likes Braddock. Result\u2014\nthe bet, and at very gallant odds.\n(Central Prw)\nCanoeist Missing\nfjj\u00df\nRichard Huertley, 17, who has been\nmissing from his home in Darien,\nConn., more than week, is pictured\nabove. He set out in an 18-foot\ncanoe, possibly headed for Florida.\nHe is the object of an intensive\nsearch.\n(CentralPrem):\nt r\nIn Three Years!\naWv>\ns r M\ns j Mr\nIrene Propheta k\nschool genius, in 3 years\nThree years ago Irene Propheta,\nnow an 18-year-old freshman at\nHunter college, New York, ar\nrived in the United States from\nLemberg, Poland. With scarcely\nany knowledge of English, she en\ntered school. In six months she\nhad mastered the English lan\nguage. She passed all her sub\njects with highest of honors and\ngained membership in an honor\nsociety. To top that, she was\ngiven a Latin medal. A patron\nhas taken a personal interest in\nIrene and has given her work.\n\u2014Central Press\nMahogany Mary\nMary Joan Blair\nall dressed up in mahogany\nWood you know this girl? Sure\nyou wood. She is Mary Joan\nBlair. She\u2019s modeling in wood\nto be exact\u2014in mahogany robes\nand crown as part of Chicago\u2019s\nfurniture show. Her throne is a\nChippendale chair made from\nwhat is said to be the oldest piece\nof mahogany in existence, 425\nyears old.\n\u2014Central Press\nTells of Job Loss\n\n~\u00a33,\nw \u00abx*ftooi<WW\u00dfo\u00df\u00df\u00df&-. .\u2022.-\"wj-;... .\u00abQvjsSQ3S'\n\u2022v w .v.*.Cxiji\nf' M|\nr ..'J\n\n\ns\nA,\nI':: 7;,\nf\nIsadore Lubin\nArmed with his charts, Isadore\nLubin, of the U. S. bureau of labor\nstatistics, appears before the spe\ncial senate committee investigat\ning unemployment, relief and the\nbusiness recession. Lubin told of\nthe unemployment gain and added\nan assertion that some firms,\nwhich in the early days of the\ndepression which began in 1929\nfollowed a policy of spreading\nwork by shortening the work\nweek of each employe, were not\ndoing so now. Another witness,\nMarriner Eccles, chairman of the\nFederal Reserve Board, told the\ncommittee that immediate re\nsumption of large-scale govern\nment spending would \u201cturn the\ntide\u201d of the business recession.\ntlubby \u201cSteals\u201d Wife From Hospital\nt\ntei?>\u2022:- V V\nTop, Mrs. Couch and daughter; below Couch and son\nBecause he objected to physicians giving his wife ether, Ben Couch,\n42, shoved physicians aside at a Wichita, Kas., hospital, took his wife\nfrom the delivery room and speeded her home in a taxicab where she\ngave birth to a five-pound daughter before a physician arrived.\nCouch denied he threatened physicians with a knife, declaring he\nmerely held a knife in his hands when he doubled up his fist, feeling\nhe would have to fight for his wife. Couch and an 18-month-old son\n?nd Mrs. Couch and her baby daughter are shown above.\nBaby Flies for Her Life\nI\nPictured in the arms of Nurse Mary C. Potter, at Utica, N. Y., is \u201cLittle\nMiss Rome,\u201d a 6-months-old baby of Rome, N. Y., as she awaited word to\nboard a plane for Baltimore. The child\u2019s esophagus is ruptured, necessi\ntating a vital operation. She is one of a poor Rome family, and expenses\nare being paid by the Rome Chamber of Commerce, which has raised\n$1,200 for th\u00abu purpose. (Central Press)\nSTAN LAUREL AND DANCER-BRIDE\nipjE 1\n\u00dcBKiiiff mmm j\ni V\nN ..X\nMr. and Mrs. Stan Laurel on honeymoon\nFirst screen personality to say \u201cI do\u201d in 1938 is Stan Laurel, the cry\nbaby half of the comic team of Laurel and Hardy. Laurel eloped to\nYuma v Ariz., with Vera Inanova Shuvalova, a Russian dancer, in\nspite of efforts of his divorced wife, Virginia Ruth Laurel, to halt the\nproceedings. Laurel had received final divorce papers the day previ\nously, but Mrs. Laurel No. 1 contested them.","height":"28362","width":"21426"}}
